_data.title: På ski i Hamlagrø
_data.introduction: Hamlagrø, located between Dale and Voss, is an area popular for hiking and skiing. This trip, we set out the ski up Mykkeltveitveten and escape the crowded city life for a while. We knew it was going to be cold, but it turned out the be very cold. The second day of the trip we managed to find a more relaxed skiing trip that made us appreciate these opportunities even more.
_data.alt: Sun setting over snowy mountains

Going down the steep initial climb was a lot of fun, and although my inexperienced butt was very attracted to the snow, we made it down fast and safely.

We drove a bit back in the direction of Bergen (now in daylight) and stopped at a parking lot located next to the frozen Hamlagrøvatnet. _data.text:
### Heading out We are always squeezing in trips where they do not necessarily fit. This Thursday we departed in the afternoon after an exhausting bouldering session (which was amazing, and there was breakfast, hurrah). Already tired, we drove from Bergen to Hamlagrøvatnet for what would be my the first actual ski trip in the mountains. I was excited. From Dale it was possible to take a mountain road to the parking lot we would spend the night. Overconfident in Ben as I am, we went for it. Luckily, the van made it over the mountain safely, but there was a healthy amount of slipping involved. ### Arrived at the location

When we got to the parking lot it was dark and empty. It bothers me that we always drive amazing roads in the dark. I should change that. It was already eight o'clock and we still had to prepare dinner. Since it was about -15°C outside, we took the petrol stove out of the van and sacrificed one person to stand in the cold whilst the other lit the woodstove in the van. It was a difficult night to stay warm.

### The adventure day

After a quick breakfast and some meal preparation for the trip (it was so cold, we did not have the patience to sit still), we set out to the peak Mykkeltveitveten (1131m). The first part of the trail consisted of prepared cross-country skiing tracks. This turned into single track after about a kilometer or two. From there on, there was a steep climb to the first summit. Make sure your skis are properly waxed, because mine were not, and it was exhausting! After crossing the first peak, the track gently sloped down and showed us beautiful scenery. We could catch our breath here. The cold temparature really made it an exhausting trip, so when the track started to climb again, we decided to only ascend half of it and turn back a few kilometers from the peak in order to make it back to Ben before darkness fell. Luckily, the return journey was not as steep anymore. Going down the steep initial climb was a lot of fun, and although my inexperienced butt was very attracted to the snow, we made it down fast and safely. Back at the van we chopped some wood and hopped inside. We lit the woodstove (a local told us it had been -24°C the night before) and cooked some sweet sweet potato carrot rice stew to refuel. We ended the day with some talks and reflecting on the day that had past. God, what were we tired.

### Now what? The next day we decided to keep it relaxed. It was now Saturday, and the parking lot began to fill up. At 10 o'clock it was really time to start the day. So, we did what is the hardest thing to do whilst living the Benlife: getting out of your sleeping bag and stand in the cold to make breakfast. Just porridge and coffee. We drove a bit back in the direction of Bergen (now in daylight) and stopped at a parking lot located next to the frozen Hamlagrøvatnet. Ski track over the ice showed that people had been skiing across the ice. I looked amazing and flat enough to be considered relaxing. So we did what had to be done: strap on those skis and head across. Going down to the water however, I definitely overestimated my skiing abilities and got into my first skiing accident. I will be butt hurt by this for a few days. After recuperating, it was a beatiful trip where we just enjoyed what was around us. ### Heading back

Upon return from the relaxing ski tour, we had the obligatory hot chocolate in the van. When a local came up to us and said we could not camp here, I was happy to report to him we weren't planning on doing so (for once not being stressed that we had to find a new spot). Instead, we drove back to Bergen and enjoyed that life does not always need to consist of freezing in a van on the road.

_data.description: We hiked up Preikestolen on this slightly rainy day. That meant less people, but a very dramatic view nonetheless. This was a truely beautiful and not too demanding hike.
_data.title: Scaling Preikestolen
_data.alt: Abel standing on the edge of a cliff.

_data.description: After a 5 hour drive we were happy to finally arrive at the camp spot in Stavanger. We stretched our legs by running, dancing and jumping on the beach.
_data.title: Beach exploration
_data.alt: Abel running up a rock on a beach.

_data.description: When a friend gifts you a moose sticker, you directly apply it to the back of your van of course.
_data.title: Applying stickers
_data.alt: Abel applying a sticker to the backdoor of the van.

_data.description: Chocolate is just on of the most important dishes on a trip. I was enjoying the couch in the van whilst having the first chocolate bar of the trip.
_data.title: Relax and eat chocolate
_data.alt: Abel laying on the couch in the van with a chocolate bar in his hand.

_data.description: Hello world. Mornings in the van are cold, so getting dressed quickly is the key to staying warm after exiting your sleeping bag.
_data.title: Good morning face
_data.alt: Abel in bed in the van after just getting dressed.

_data.description: One of the first times the wood stove is being used to warm food. I was so excited to see these tortillas actually get a bit crispy. Go fire!
_data.title: Crispy tortillas
_data.alt: Tortillas laying on top of the wood stove.

_data.description: The hike to Trolltunga was a beautiful, but rather tough one. I remember my knee aching slightly near the end, but this crew managed to get us there.
_data.title: The hiking crew
_data.alt: The line-up of friends hiking to Trolltunga with their backpacks looking into the distance.

_data.description: We found this idyllic mountain road to camp. Because some friends were delayed by car trouble, we pitched two tents for them at the water side already.
_data.title: Camping at roadside
_data.alt: The van and a car parked next to a gravel road.

_data.description: What a beautiful sunset can be seen from Trolltunga. This was from the spot where we were camping for the night. Can you believe that?
_data.title: A Trolltunga sunset
_data.alt: The sunset with the lake that can be seen from Trolltunga.

_data.description: Waking up in nature gives such a peaceful touch to your morning. There is no place to be, except for the place where you are right now.
_data.title: Waking up with a view
_data.alt: Abel laying in a tent in the morning staring at the nice view outside.
